What evidential languages give you is a linguistic enforcement layer for that philosophy.

Let’s make it concrete.

⸻

1. The Core Insight

Evidential languages don’t ask:

“Is this true?”

They ask:

“How do you know?”

That shift maps perfectly to Pantheon doctrine:
	•	Truth ≠ Authority claim
	•	Truth = Source traceability + epistemic category + reversible stance

So instead of policing content, you scaffold epistemic metadata.

That’s very Pantheon.

⸻

2. Pantheon Evidential Layer (PEL v0.1)

Add a lightweight required tag to all major claims:

Every Claim Must Carry:
	•	Source Class
	•	Confidence Range
	•	Transform Type (observed / inferred / modeled / symbolic / narrative)

Example:

“AI will end capitalism.”
Would require tagging:

	•	Source Class: speculative synthesis
	•	Transform Type: narrative extrapolation
	•	Confidence: low–medium
	•	Evidence Mode: model inference

Now it becomes structured instead of mythic drift.

⸻

3. Map It to Existing Pantheon Systems

Checksum → Verifies claim lineage

Evidential tag becomes part of the hash.

Merkle Warden → Stores epistemic metadata

Claims are content-addressed + evidence-addressed.

Mirror.guard → Ensures epistemic category consistency

Prevents:
	•	Observational claims presented as inevitabilities
	•	Symbolic metaphors presented as literal prediction
	•	Narrative compression mistaken for empirical evidence

Hound → Flags mismatched evidential category

If someone:
	•	States speculation as fact
	•	Uses authority language without source tag
	•	Collapses inference into observation

Hound trips anomaly.

⸻

4. This Directly Strengthens PNIS

PNIS already says:

Certify process, not truth.

Evidential tagging formalizes that.

You aren’t saying:

